The West Nile virus is a mosquito-borne virus that can cause encephalitis or inflammation of the brain.
West Nile encephalitis cannot be passed from person to person, or from birds to people; the virus must pass through a mosquito.
This year the virus has appeared only in birds and mosquitoes - bloodsucking insects that can spread West Nile to humans.
Last summer an outbreak of the West Nile virus killed seven people in Queens, N.Y., and sickened more than 60 others.
Victims of West Nile virus typically experience flu-like symptoms.
Some people who are infected with West Nile virus show no symptoms, but others suffer from flu-like symptoms.
Ticks infected with West Nile virus have been found in Asia and Africa.
